{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528482"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14305"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14305"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.81,0.04,0.01,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7000"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39938"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4353"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine antenatal visit at 36 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only prenatal vitamins. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The fundal height measures 35 cm. On abdominal palpation, the fetal head is palpable in the fundal region, and the fetal heartbeat is auscultated in the upper abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis based on the clinical findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transverse lie","Breech presentation","Oblique lie","Unstable lie","Cephalic presentation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical findings in this case are consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebreech presentation\u003C/strong\u003E. In a breech presentation, the fetus\u0027s buttocks or feet are positioned to enter the birth canal first, rather than the head. The palpation of the fetal head in the fundal region and the auscultation of the fetal heartbeat in the upper abdomen are indicative of this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecephalic presentation\u003C/strong\u003E is the normal fetal position where the head is positioned to enter the birth canal first. This is ruled out by the clinical examination findings, which clearly show the fetal head in the fundal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse lie\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when the fetus is positioned horizontally across the uterus. This would present differently on clinical examination, with the fetal pole felt in the maternal flanks rather than at the fundus and lower uterine segment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoblique lie\u003C/strong\u003E is when the long axis of the fetus is diagonal to the long axis of the mother. This is an unstable position and is usually transient, often converting to either a longitudinal or transverse lie.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eunstable lie\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a situation where the fetal presentation changes frequently, often due to factors such as polyhydramnios or multiparity. While this is a possibility, the findings described are consistent with a stable breech presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while clinical examination can suggest a breech presentation, ultrasound is the gold standard for confirming fetal presentation and distinguishing between the different types of breech (frank, complete, or footling). Breech presentation occurs in approximately 3-4% of term pregnancies. Diagnosing breech presentation is crucial as it may influence the management of labour and delivery, potentially necessitating interventions such as external cephalic version or planned caesarean section.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Breech presentation occurs in approximately 3-4% of term pregnancies.","Ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing fetal presentation and distinguishing between types of breech presentation.","The three types of breech presentation are frank breech, complete breech, and footling breech."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Management of breech presentation at term [Internet]. East Melbourne (Australia): RANZCOG; 2016. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Management-Breech-Presentation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39938"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14305"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39938"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T17:36:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T17:37:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7000"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati